<main>
  <!-- BENEFITS -->
  <section id="benefits">
    <h2>Why Weightlifting Is Safe and Beneficial</h2>
    <p>Modern research from pediatric and sports medicine groups shows that well‑designed resistance training programs are safe for adolescents and can improve strength, bone health, body composition, performance, and self‑esteem while helping prevent sports injuries.</p>

    <div class="grid grid-3" style="margin-top: 1rem;">
      <article class="card">
        <h3>Physical Health</h3>
        <small>Strong muscles, strong bones</small>
        <ul>
          >Increases muscular strength and power for daily life and sports. [web:31][web:34]</li>
          >Improves bone strength and mineral content, supporting healthy growth. [web:31][web:34]</li>
          >Helps maintain healthy blood pressure and cholesterol levels. [web:37]</li>
          >Supports healthy body composition and decreases adiposity over time. [web:31]</li>
        </ul>
      </article>

      <article class="card">
        <h3>Injury Protection</h3>
        <small>More resilient joints</small>
        <ul>
          >Strengthens muscles, tendons, and ligaments around joints, lowering injury risk. [web:31][web:34]</li>
          >Improves movement control, balance, and landing mechanics. [web:32][web:35]</li>
          >Builds “strength reserves” so practices and games are less stressful on tissues. [web:34][web:40]</li>
        </ul>
      </article>

      <article class="card">
        <h3>Mental & Social</h3>
        <small>Confidence and consistency</small>
        <ul>
          >Boosts self‑esteem and confidence as strength and skills improve. [web:31][web:34]</li>
          >Introduces a structured habit that can track into adulthood. [web:31][web:34]</li>
          >Can be an accessible on‑ramp to more physical activity for inactive teens. [web:31]</li>
        </ul>
      </article>
    </div>

    <div class="card" style="margin-top: 1.25rem;">
      <p class="label-danger">Myth check</p>
      <p>Well‑programmed resistance training has not been shown to stunt growth or damage growth plates when supervision, proper technique, and age‑appropriate loads are used.</p>
      <p style="font-size:0.85rem; color: var(--muted); margin-top:0.4rem;">Always work with a qualified coach or physical education teacher if possible, especially when learning free‑weight exercises.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- INJURY PREVENTION / EXERCISES -->
  <section id="injury-prevention">
    <h2>Key Exercises for Injury Prevention</h2>
    <p>These exercise categories help protect common problem areas for adolescent athletes, especially the knees, shoulders, and lower back, when combined with good warm‑ups and gradual progression.</p>

    <div class="grid grid-2" style="margin-top: 1rem;">
      <article class="card">
        <h3>Knee & Ankle Protection</h3>
        <span class="pill"><strong>Focus</strong> Jumps, landings, change of direction</span>
        <ul>
          ><strong>Bodyweight squat</strong> – Learn to sit back and keep knees tracking over toes for safe loading. [web:32]</li>
          ><strong>Reverse and walking lunges</strong> – Strengthen quads and glutes while training knee alignment. [web:32][web:35]</li>
          ><strong>Single‑leg squat or step‑down</strong> – Improves hip and knee stability on one leg. [web:35]</li>
          ><strong>Calf raises</strong> – Support ankles and Achilles tendon, important for running and jumping. [web:32]</li>
        </ul>
      </article>

      <article class="card">
        <h3>Shoulder & Upper‑Body Protection</h3>
        <span class="pill"><strong>Focus</strong> Pressing and overhead work</span>
        <ul>
          ><strong>Push‑ups</strong> – Build pressing strength with good shoulder position before using weights. [web:32]</li>
          ><strong>Dumbbell row</strong> – Strengthens upper‑back muscles that support shoulder blades. [web:32]</li>
          ><strong>Band pull‑apart / face pull</strong> – Helps prevent rounded shoulders and imbalances. [web:32]</li>
          ><strong>Shoulder circles & arm swings</strong> – Dynamic warm‑up for fluid shoulder motion. [web:32]</li>
        </ul>
      </article>
    </div>

    <div class="grid grid-2" style="margin-top: 1.25rem;">
      <article class="card">
        <h3>Core & Lower Back Protection</h3>
        <span class="pill"><strong>Focus</strong> Stable spine under load</span>
        <ul>
          ><strong>Front plank & side plank</strong> – Train core endurance for safe squats and deadlifts. [web:32][web:35]</li>
          ><strong>Bird dog</strong> – Teaches hip and shoulder movement while the spine stays stable. [web:32]</li>
          ><strong>Hip hinge with dowel</strong> – Practice deadlift pattern without heavy weight first. [web:31]</li>
          ><strong>Glute bridge</strong> – Activates glutes to help protect the lower back. [web:32]</li>
        </ul>
      </article>

      <article class="card">
        <h3>Mobility & Stretching</h3>
        <span class="pill"><strong>Focus</strong> Flexible, balanced muscles</span>
        <ul>
          ><strong>Dynamic warm‑up</strong> – Light jog, high knees, butt kicks, and leg swings before lifting. [web:32][web:38]</li>
          ><strong>Hamstring stretch</strong> – Reduces tightness that can pull on the low back. [web:38]</li>
          ><strong>Hip flexor and quad stretch</strong> – Counteracts long periods of sitting and sports loading. [web:35][web:38]</li>
          ><strong>Chest and shoulder stretches</strong> – Help keep posture balanced with pushing exercises. [web:32]</li>
        </ul>
      </article>
    </div>

    <div class="table-wrapper" style="margin-top:1.25rem;">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Area</th>
