  <section id="technique">
    <h2>Form and Technique Basics</h2>
    <p>Good technique allows you to get stronger while protecting your joints and spine, and it always matters more than how much weight is on the bar.</p>

    <div class="form-img-row" style="margin-top:1rem;">
      <div class="form-list">
        <h3>Squat Technique Checklist</h3>
        <ul>
          ><strong>Stance</strong>: Feet about shoulder‑width apart, toes slightly turned out.</li>
          ><strong>Bracing</strong>: Take a breath “into your belly,” gently tighten your core before you move.</li>
          ><strong>Movement</strong>: Sit hips back and down like a controlled “sit to chair,” chest facing forward.</li>
          ><strong>Knees</strong>: Track knees over 2nd–3rd toe, do not let them cave inward.</li>
          ><strong>Depth</strong>: Go as low as you can while maintaining a flat back and heel contact with the floor.</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="form-tip">Use a box or bench behind you at first to learn consistent depth and safe control. [web:32]</p>

        <h3 style="margin-top:1rem;">Hip Hinge / Deadlift Pattern</h3>
        <ul>
          ><strong>Neutral spine</strong>: Keep your back flat from head to hips, avoiding rounding or hyper‑arching. [web:31]</li>
          ><strong>Hips first</strong>: Push hips back while softening your knees rather than bending mostly at the knees.</li>
          ><strong>Bar or weights close</strong>: Keep weights close to shins and thighs to protect the lower back. [web:31]</li>
          ><strong>Stand tall</strong>: Drive through mid‑foot and heels to stand up, squeezing glutes at the top.</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="form-tip">Practice with a dowel or broomstick along your back (touching head, upper back, and hips) to feel a neutral spine as you hinge. [web:31]</p>
      </div>

